# Distributed Web Infrastructure

## For every additional element, why you are adding it

* **DNS Server:** Required to resolve the domain name ([www.foobar.com](http://www.foobar.com)) to an IP address.
* **Load Balancer (HAProxy):** Distributes incoming traffic across multiple servers, prevents any single server from being overwhelmed, and improves availability.
* **Two Web/Application Servers:** Allow horizontal scaling and high availability. If one server fails, the other can continue serving traffic.
* **Primary-Replica Database Cluster:** Provides data redundancy and improves read performance by replicating data from the Primary database to the Replica database.

---

## What distribution algorithm your load balancer is configured with and how it works

The load balancer is configured with the **Round Robin** algorithm.

Round Robin distributes requests across servers in a rotation system. The first request goes to Server 1, the second request goes to Server 2, the third request goes back to Server 1, and so on.

---

## Is your load balancer enabling an Active-Active or Active-Passive setup? Explain the difference.

The load balancer is configured in an **Active-Active** setup because both servers actively receive traffic.

* **Active-Active:** All servers are active and handle requests at the same time. If one server fails, the others continue serving traffic.
* **Active-Passive:** Only one server handles traffic while the second server remains on standby and takes over if the active server fails.

---

## How a database Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) cluster works

The Primary-Replica database setup works by having the **Primary (Master)** database handle all write operations such as INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE.

The **Replica (Slave)** database receives copies of the data from the Primary through replication. This provides redundancy and can improve read performance by offloading read queries to the Replica.

If the Primary database fails, a Replica can be promoted to become the new Primary.

---

## What is the difference between the Primary node and the Replica node in regard to the application

* **Primary (Master):** Handles both read and write operations.
* **Replica (Slave):** Usually handles read operations only and maintains a copy of the Primary database.

---

## What are the issues with this infrastructure?

### Where are SPOF (Single Points of Failure)?

* The **Load Balancer** is a Single Point of Failure because if it fails, users cannot reach the servers.
* The **Primary Database** is also a Single Point of Failure because if it fails, write operations cannot be performed.

### Security issues

* No firewall to filter incoming traffic.
* No HTTPS, so data is transmitted unencrypted between the client and the server.
* This exposes data to eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle attacks.

### No monitoring

There is no monitoring system to track server health, application performance, or database status.

Failures may go unnoticed until users report them.
